text: Saw this yesterday. Even for a drama, it was boring.  The pace felt like it picked up for a 10 minute period in the middle, and then it just dropped back down to a snail's pace.  There was a scene where Lee goes to see his dead brother's body and you just sit there with the camera staring at Lee and a doctor as other person slowly takes the body out so he can see it.  Like... you couldn't cut some of this shit out?  Or the part later in the movie where a person is being placed in an ambulance via stretcher, but the paramedics seems to have never used one of those stretchers before so they have a difficult time putting it in the ambulance.  What's the point of showing us this stuff?  And then, in the end, the entire film just ended up feeling like a complete waste of time because the story goes nowhere and there isn't a real ending... it just ends.  Also, Michelle Williams was on screen for like 5 minutes total.  Her character is sick in half of that, and crying the other half.  I don't know if that deserves a fourth Oscar nomination.

text: I think the only people saying they really like this movie must have seen a different cut of it than played in my theater, or they're hyping it for reasons known only to them. Every person in the theater that I could hear was in disbelief when the credits started to flash, and like me, were surprised that it was getting such positive hype in the media. text: i didn't fall for it. the whole movie, it just felt forced. not fake but, something about the plot just felt off. was it based on a book? coz that would make sense. if it was an original script, it was solely made just for the academy to praise it. the acting also, i'm ot saying it was bad, but in my opinion it felt pretty staged; and the music side was unsettling, fitted and shoved into the film like, i don't even know what could've possibly gone through the music director's mind, to be honest, but it would've been way more real without any of it.. at least not during those scenes, you know what i mean? it's a drama, but you dont nessesarily need to play dramatic music over an already pretty dramatic scene where there's very dramatic dialog going on. it felt as if the dialog was the dramatic background noise to the melody itself. that could've been easily fixed in editing, but for some reason they didn't- there's art in it, i can tell you that, but i still can't tell whether this constitutes yet another typical oscar aimed and made "masterpiece", an actual masterpiece or a downright hot mess.

text: I have recently seen Manchester by the Sea. I gather it's located in the US state of Massachusetts, which continues the Boston-based films that both Affleck brothers have been involved in. Casey Affleck takes on a responsibility that he is unused to and ill-prepared for: the guardianship of a 16 year-old nephew.  The film portrays a limited man, an inexpressive unsociable blue-collar man who jars with others and tends to erupt into fist fights at bars at the slightest provocation. I tended to dislike this aspect of the character, but Casey Affleck plays the role flawlessly. I like a film of a family crisis where characters' emotions are revealed, where conflict is dealt with an resolved. The fishing boat is a place of nostalgia for the characters. I was confused by a lot of the flashbacks to about 10 years earlier. I was also confused by the seminal 'disaster' incident in the film involving Affleck's carelessness when he went out to buy more beers. Where does that fit in? Some cinema viewers last night were audibly upset, shedding tears, but I felt little empathy for the Affleck character. Is he a schmuck, a misfit, a laudable Joe 6-pack out of his depth or just a brawler with whom we have little feeling for? In my case, he is the last named. Look for a small role for Matthew Broderick, Ferris Bueller himself, looking silver-haired and middle-aged but watchable, as the nephew's mom's new man.

text: Hello.  In the 1950's in Gloucester, Massachusetts, which is just a 15 minute drive from Manchester-by-the-Sea, a similarly tragic event happened. My husband was a boy when it happened, but he remembers it well. He said that there are so many similarities and parallels in this movie to what happened to three boys and their parents, who were his family's close friends and neighbors across the street, that this tragic story could have been based on what sadly happened to them.   Out of a respect for the privacy of any family that this may have happened to, including what happened to my husband's friends and neighbors, it is best to empathetically remain thoughtfully quiet, think kind and wishes of them, and go without mentioning their names.

text: I think that maybe A LOT of people got duped into thinking that Casey Affleck's performance was something truly extraordinary in Manchester By the Sea.  People keep saying that "it was such understated and subtle work" but you could also call that "doing little" truly.  He had no big emotional or powerful moments or tour-de-force-type scenes in the movie that are typically distinctive of Oscar-winning performances -- not ONE.  Yes, I think that perhaps a lot of people drank the "Casey Affleck was brilliant in Manchester By the Sea" Kool-Aid this year.  (Oh, I forgot...he ACTUALLY did come to life once in the movie...after he was interrogated at the police station...my bad.)

text: I give this movie a thumbs up, but it's a weak thumbs up. Talk about an extremely overrated movie. Casey Affleck winning best actor is absurd. He's an above average actor, however in this movie, his sad moments scenes he struggles with in a big way. I get it, his character was supposed to be dead inside and it's intention was supposed to be someone who hides their emotions, so I get it, but an actor should be able to obviously hide the verbal emotions, but should give us some sort of emotion that is being held back. He's just flat in the sad scenes. His reaction at the fire scene is pathetic, which btw was before he was dead inside. Couldn't they have done more takes? His best and only scene where he gives any sad emotion is when he runs into his ex wife while he's out walking around. He was good in that scene. Any other scene that should have been sad, felt like nothing. I don't understand how others didn't get the same vibe. He is definitely a very good actor that should be in demand for certain roles all of which shouldn't be a character that has to convey sadness at any point.

text: No hope, no love, no future https://drjacquescoulardeau.blogspot.fr/ KENNETH LONERGAN – MANCHESTER BY THE SEA - 2016  They have declared in all possible ways this film is a master piece, and it is just my luck: it is. They have declared the main actor to be best actor in I don’t know how many places, at least three times, and it is just my luck: he is a very good actor. Best I don’t know, but very good that’s sure. And yet that’s not enough bad luck since even the most important part of this film is at least twice said to be the best original scenario. Only twice, true enough. Hooray! So here I can be the third guy of the triad. The subject of this film is fascinating. Some will say it is banal, and it is. It happens all the time and every day, and yet it is mesmerizing because it is a subject so few people would ever speak of, deal with, make a film from. […]
